      <bioghist id="aspace_501d40ec29602f4522be47f978635ac2">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>David Joseph Piel was born on July 10, 1923, in New York City. He attended Taft School in Watertown, Connecticut, and entered Yale in July 1942. He enlisted in the United States Marine Corps, went overseas in November 1944, and became a combat radio correspondent with the lst Marine Division, 5th Battalion. He served in the Pacific Theater, including Okinawa. After Japan's surrender, he was assigned to Special Services in Peiping. Discharged from military service in March 1946, Piel returned to Yale. Upon graduation, he worked in advertising and television in New York and San Francisco, producing story films for the Captain Kangaroo show, as well as acting in television and radio commercials. Piel died of lung cancer in Carson City, Nevada, May 2004.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_846e042053d5e85477c9c9167366daaa">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The papers include bound sketchbooks of watercolor drawings and captions by David Piel depicting military and local civilian life during World War II in the South Pacific, as well as related correspondence, memorabilia, military transmittals, newspaper clippings, and photographs.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_0e33ba55362ff7e9a5fd251db3136258">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Arranged by type of material. Sketchbooks are listed alphabetically by title, and oversize materials are at the end of the inventory.</p>  
      </arrangement>
  
